n style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While progress has been made in improving the lives of people with disabilities in developing countries, it is accepted that people with disabilities still remain largely invisible in mainstream development. It is essential that the mistakes of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Millenn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ium </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evelopment Goals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which failed to name people with disabilities, are not repeated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The United Nations Convention on the Rights of persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (UNCRPD)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">adopted by the General Assembly in 2006 and ratified by the European Union in 2010, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s the first human rights treaty of the 21st century. Countries that sign and ratify the convention  commit to promoting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and protecting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the rights and dignity of people with disabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The UK ratified the convention in 2009.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The convention has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specific article relating to International Cooperation (article 32)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This provides signatories with a normative framework to mainstream disability in the international development agenda.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> normative framework and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">existing platforms for shaping a p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ost </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2015 MDG agenda that is tru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly inclusive of disability issues </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">present DfID with a unique opportunity to feed into this debate. DfID's involvement can in turn help shape the future of its policy that can help mainstream disability issues in its existing prog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rammes and support the development of disability specific programmes.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Livability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> www.livability.org</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.uk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provides a range of care, support and community inclusion services for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and campaigns for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> full inclusion into society. Since 1995 the organisation has worked in low resourced countries across Asia with the aim of increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the quality and coverage of essential healthcare, rehabilitation and community inclusion services for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people with disabil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ities.  Without</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these services many people would not survive. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reason for maki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng this submission is to advocate for greater inclusion of people with disabilities within all DfID programmes and to promote a DfID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and Development</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">According to the W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orld Health Organisation (W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Persons with disabilities, particularly those in developing countries, experience a poorer health status, as well as higher rates of poverty, lower rates of employment, increased depend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ency and restricted participation. Persons with disabilities face widespread barriers... Many of the barriers experienced by persons with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">disabilities are avoidable and the disadvantage associated with disability can be overcome”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Livability have worked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the field of international disability and development for almost 2 decades. While we have seen many positive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> developments in relation to an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services and opportunities we are also aware that many people with disability still face huge barrier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s in realising their most basic human rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Livability have concentrated on increasing the quality and coverage of healthcare, rehabilitation and community inclusion services in developing countries. Our experience has been that when appropriate, health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">care, rehabilitation and community services are provided, people with disability, even in low resourced environments, can live full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> meaningful and inclusive lives. We have found that people want services and the opportunity to work not charity and hand-ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is unfortunately still the case however that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people with disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">excluded from mainstream services and development programmes. Specialised services and rehabilitation programmes  are still few and far between.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When these services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are not available poverty and social marginalisation increase. The perso</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n with disability often develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s physical and psychological </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> life threatening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">complications and requires care. The burden of care </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> falls on the female members within the househ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">old and the family sinks further into despair.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">According to the recently published WHO/I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nternational Spinal Cord Society </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> entitled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">International Perspectives on Spinal Cord Injuries,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">isconceptions, negative attitudes and physical barriers to basi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c mobility result in the exclusion of many people from full participation in society. The report discovered that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, many people with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pinal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ord </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">njury and other disabilities are excluded from work and livelihood opportunities, with the result that they and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">their families live in poverty and are marginalized from the mainstream of society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability and International Development Aid:</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Estimates suggest there are more than one billion disabled people, but less than four per cent of them benefit from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">international development assistance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However many of the countries wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ich</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provide development assistance are signatories to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NCRPD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is an international human rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> legally binding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> agreement to protect and promote the human rights of disabled pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ople throughout the world. All signatories must take concrete action to comply with the legal rights and obligations contained in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UNCRPD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The UK government ratified the Convention in June 2009. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ticle 32 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Convention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provides a comprehensive and normative framework that provides a structure whereby disability issues can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incorporated into DfID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">'s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">international cooperation programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pecific measures include:</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0e2346; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ensuring that international cooperation, including inter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national development programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inclusive of and accessible to persons with disabilities;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0e2346; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Facilitating and supporting capacity-building, including through the exchange and sharing of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information, experiences, training programmes and best practices;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0e2346; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Facilitating cooperation in research and access to scientific and technical knowledge;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0e2346; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Providing, as appropriate, technical and economic assistance, including by facilitating access to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and sharing of accessible and assistive technologies, and through the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transfer of technologies.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Disability and International Development:</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although DFID </span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is a sign</span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tory to the </span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onvention and </span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">aims to “work to end extreme poverty” and targets areas such as education, health, and economic growth it does not as yet have a </span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">coherent, time-bound, measurable and resourced strategy for disability-inclusive development.</span><span style="color:#1a171b; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The disabled academic and writer Tom Shakespeare, who was one of the authors of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the World Report on Disability sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ys </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“It’s very good news that the House of Common</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s international development committee are doing an inquiry i</span><span 