services and internationally comparable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">data on disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While there is huge need for increased </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coverage and quality of accessible, appropriate and affordable rehabilitation services for children and adults with disabilities few international development agencies target the development of such services as a strategic priority.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfID could play an imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ortant role in helping to fill this gap. UK rehabilitation and service provision organisations are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">well placed to support  technical and human resource  capacity developments of partners overseas.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">In relation to the issue of the role of disabled bene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ficiaries in planning, managing and monitoring DFID policy and programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">:</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People with disabilities and their representative organisations are well placed to advise on the development of policy, programmes and services. Many people with disabilities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developing countries have first</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hand experience of what it is like not to have access to the services they need. People with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recognised role in monitoring levels of implementation of UNCRPD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to feed into established monitoring m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">echanisms.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When DfID is in the process of designing new or reviewing existing country, regional and international programmes, disability specific questions should be asked and people with disabilities and their representative organisations consulted. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; f